<paragraph id="0DFA8E46CAA12D43B547D35096262A5D" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">No data.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FB7365BE03EEC9797200CBCF27BE8276" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="20C61192B4DB8335FFDBF800C927464C" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F0A27171F970905BADDABE646B721CB7" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Adriatic. So far there is only a single record of this species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7DE522DB1159FB2CEDA439B409C64208" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="7D9F60D1BEB040B8F65A95F39C9AD091" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C04619122F4BAB014E91A199DAD6AF3" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
A major difference with the original description is the lack of giant oxeas (4000 
<normalizedToken id="1C163A6C113319A0B37067089F58280E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
70 
<normalizedToken id="55A575DA1416879600FAFA8B34503F66" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
), some centrotylote, reported and pictured by 
<bibRefCitation id="D955DF650F3C517DEECC2B4AB1B06549" author="Lendenfeld, R von" journalOrPublisher="Denkschriften der Kaiserlichen Akademie der Wissenschaften Wien, Mathematisch-Naturwissenschaften Klasse" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="91 - 204" title="Die Tetractinelliden der Adria. (Mit einem Anhange ueber die Lithistiden)." volume="61" year="1894">Lendenfeld (1894)</bibRefCitation>
; also tylostyles and strongyles were reported. The fragment of the type specimen received from ZMB did not contain any such spicules, except for some broken fragments. For 
<bibRefCitation id="A3C2B98DFC9333B93C44D6AA4C9DCA29" author="Maldonado, M" editor="Hooper, JNA" journalOrPublisher="Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publications, New York" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="141 - 162" title="Pachastrellidae" volumeTitle="Systema Porifera. A guide to the classification of sponges" year="2002">Maldonado (2002)</bibRefCitation>
the alleged presence of oxeas in a species otherwise considered by him a typical 
<taxonomicName id="2335DA3621938FF3BF06AEBF65CBD86D" authority="Sollas, 1888" authorityName="Sollas" authorityYear="1888" class="Demospongiae" family="Pachastrellidae" genus="Stoeba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stoeba" order="Astrophorida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">Stoeba</taxonomicName>
was the reason to accept species with structural monaxone megascleres within the definition of 
<taxonomicName id="CC1ECE875A2E8DC97A54096990B4D6E0" authority="Sollas, 1888" authorityName="Sollas" authorityYear="1888" class="Demospongiae" family="Pachastrellidae" genus="Stoeba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stoeba" order="Astrophorida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">Stoeba</taxonomicName>
. We maintain that such spicules, if they would be proper, are auxiliary, not structural.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0E26BDC8D6AE03597197EB6C0F685AB0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
This species is similar in most respects to 
<taxonomicName id="F3E0AC91C6E3A40472612E95B3BE5DC0" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Dercitus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dercitus (Stoeba) plicatus" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="plicatus" subGenus="Stoeba">Dercitus (Stoeba) plicatus</taxonomicName>
, but the orange colour has not been reported for that species (although 
<bibRefCitation id="486B3918768DA580AEECAF68A431C1C4" author="Pulitzer-Finali, G" journalOrPublisher="Annali del Museo civico di storia naturale Giacomo Doria" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="445 - 621" title="A collection of Mediterranean Demospongiae (Porifera) with, in appendix, a list of the Demospongiae hitherto recorded from the Mediterranean Sea." volume="84" year="1983">Pulitzer-Finali (1983)</bibRefCitation>
mentions brown specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="A8033D8F8FF5184B2E078F6C59791D3A" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Dercitus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dercitus (Stoeba) plicatus" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="plicatus" subGenus="Stoeba">Dercitus (Stoeba) plicatus</taxonomicName>
). Based on our observations of the sanidasters, it is possible that these are slightly different from 
<taxonomicName id="2090059479BD7061557DD90269CDEF32" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Dercitus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dercitus (Stoeba) plicatus" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="plicatus" subGenus="Stoeba">Dercitus (Stoeba) plicatus</taxonomicName>
in spination, with the latter having more profused spines. In view of this, we are forced to retain 
<taxonomicName id="471E03B704DEFB5613E511DBF6E396E8" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Dercitus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dercitus (Stoeba) lesinensis" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lesinensis" subGenus="Stoeba">Dercitus (Stoeba) lesinensis</taxonomicName>
as a valid species for the time being.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
